>
  <p>
    Discounts are the most manipulated number in retail. A price can be "reduced"
    without anything actually changing, because the discount is measured against a
    reference price the seller chose. Once you know how that trick works, you can
    see through most of it in about thirty seconds.
  </p>

  <h2>The anchor: where "50% off" really comes from</h2>
  <p>
    Nearly every discount is a comparison between two numbers: the price you pay and
    a higher "was" price crossed out beside it. That crossed-out number is called
    the anchor, and it does an enormous amount of psychological work — it makes the
    sale price feel like a rescue.
  </p>
  <p>
    The problem: the anchor is often fiction. It might be a "manufacturer's
    suggested retail price" the product never actually sold at, or a brief,
    strategic high price set just long enough to justify a permanent "sale." When
    the anchor is inflated, the discount is theater. The real question is never
    "how big is the discount?" — it's "<strong>is the price I'd pay a good price
    for this thing?</strong>"
  </p>

  <h2>Check the price history</h2>
  <p>
    The fastest way to expose a fake sale is to look at what the product has
    actually cost over time. Browser extensions and price-tracking sites chart the
    price history for many popular items, and the pattern is usually obvious at a
    glance:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>A genuine deal</strong> shows a price that's clearly below its normal
      band — a real dip you'd be lucky to catch.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>A fake deal</strong> shows a "sale" price that's simply the price the
      product sits at most of the time, with the anchor floating above it,
      permanently crossed out.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If the "sale" price is the same price it was last month and the month before,
    the urgency is manufactured.
  </p>

  <h2>Time it: when things actually go on sale</h2>
  <p>
    Real discounts follow predictable calendars, because retailers clear inventory
    on a schedule:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Seasonal gear</strong> is cheapest at the end of its season — garden and outdoor equipment in autumn, winter coats in late winter.</li>
    <li><strong>Electronics</strong> cluster around major sales events and new-model launches, when last year's version is marked down to move.</li>
    <li><strong>Everyday goods</strong> rarely need to be bought at full price if you can wait a few weeks for the next promotional cycle.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you're not in a hurry, timing alone can beat almost any "flash" discount.
  </p>

  <h2>Spot the pressure tactics</h2>
  <p>
    Manufactured urgency is the tell that someone wants you to skip the comparison
    step. Treat these with suspicion:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Countdown timers</strong> that reset when you reload the page. A real deadline doesn't restart for each visitor.</li>
    <li><strong>"Only 3 left!"</strong> counters that never seem to hit zero, or that reappear on your next visit.</li>
    <li><strong>Perpetual sales</strong> — a store where everything is always "60% off" has simply set that as its pricing.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Genuine scarcity exists — real clearances, real seasonal windows, real
    limited stock — but it doesn't need a flashing timer to be true. When the
    pressure is loudest, slow down.
  </p>

  <h2>What a real deal looks like</h2>
  <p>
    A discount is worth acting on when three things line up: the underlying product
    is genuinely good, the price you'd pay is low relative to its own history, and
    the offer is real rather than a permanent markdown dressed as an event. Miss
    any of the three and a big percentage-off number means nothing.
  </p>

  <h2>Our rule on the deals we show</h2>
  <p>
    This is why our <a href="/how-we-rate/">rating methodology</a> treats value —
    not the size of the discount — as what matters, and why we only display
    genuine, currently-running offers. We don't run fake countdowns or invent
    "was" prices to make a deal look bigger than it is. A price is either a good
    use of your money or it isn't, and no amount of strike-through styling changes
    the answer.
  </p>
